snippet.textDisplay:
I could not, for the life of me, understand what a “jevra, gevra, xevra, jebra, gebra, or xebra” was until Genius came out with the lyrics.

I know that “Gera” is short for “Gerardo” just as “Chuey” is short for “Jesus,” but that would not explain the “v” sound.

It is speculated that Joyner was trying to say “hembra,” which is the colloquial term for a female. The correct pronunciation of “hembra” is “em-bra.”

So I was thinking that maybe he was saying it with an American accent because of the “h” sound. But then why and how did he say “Moreno,” “Gringo,” and “Vato” correctly? Is it some niche dialect that not even Urban Dictionary can decipher?

I’m at a loss. Probably just a verbal typo. Just an honest mistake. Or maybe I’m just being ignorant and going on a needless rant for no reason. Maybe I’m just out of the loop and don’t know enough about my father’s native tongue to know. I don’t know. Just saying, “jevra” is driving me insane.

Edit: If you’ve been around long enough, you’ll know that in his Gucci Gang Remix he said “I don’t know Spanish, but I know the lingo.” I guess that explains it. It’s good enough for me, anyway.

My final speculation:

Joyner knows the lingo, but he does not know Spanish too well, so he does not know that the ‘h’ is always silent. It’s an honest mistake, but he gladly embraces it because mistakes make us human. Why worry about a consonant when you can enjoy the song?

Eat your cereal
